$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\dfrac{7x-\sin(x)}{x^2+\sin(3x)}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dx}[7x-\sin(x)]}{\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^2+\sin(3x)]}\qquad\gray{\text{L’Hôpital’s rule}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\dfrac{7-\cos(x)}{2x+3\cos(3x)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{7-\cos(0)}{2(0)+3\cos(3\cdot0)}\qquad\gray{\text{Substitution}}
\\\\
&=2
\end{align}$

Note that we were only able to use L’Hôpital’s rule because the limit $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0}\dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dx}[7x-\sin(x)]}{\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^2+\sin(3x)]}$ actually exists.

$\begin{align}
