$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\dfrac{xe^{x}-e}{x^2-1}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dx}[xe^{x}-e]}{\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^2-1]}\qquad\gray{\text{L’Hôpital’s rule}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\dfrac{e^x+xe^x}{2x}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{e^{(1)}+(1)e^{(1)}}{2(1)}\qquad\gray{\text{Substitution}}
\\\\
&=e
\end{align}$

Note that we were only able to use L’Hôpital’s rule because the limit $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1}\dfrac{\dfrac{d}{dx}[xe^{x}-e]}{\dfrac{d}{dx}[x^2-1]}$ actually exists.

